ffith]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Stanner E.V. Taylor]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by D. W. Griffith]]\n[[Category:Surviving American silent films]]\n\n{{1900s-short-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1908 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Where the Breakers Roar\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[D. W. Griffith]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = D. W. Griffith<br>[[Stanner E.V. Taylor]]\n| starring       = [[Arthur V. Johnson]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[G. W. Bitzer]]<br>[[Arthur Marvin]]\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|1908|9|22}}\n| runtime        = 9 minutes (one [[Reel#Motion picture terminology|reel]])\n| country        = United States\n| language       = Silent\n}}\n\n'''''Where the Breakers Roar''''' is a 1908 American [[silent film|silent]] [[short film|short]] [[drama film]] directed by [[D. W. Griffith]]. A print of the film exists in the film archive of the [[Library of Congress]].<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/W/WhereBreakersRoar1908.html |title=Where the Breakers Roar |accessdate=December 31, 2013 |work=Silent Era}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Arthur V. Johnson]] as Tom Hudson\n* [[Linda Arvidson]] as Alice Fairchild\n* [[Charles Inslee]] as The Villain\n* [[Edward Dillon (actor)|Edward Dillon]] as Policeman\n* [[George Gebhardt]] as At the Beach / Assaulted Man\n* [[Robert Harron]] as On Boardwalk\n* [[Guy Hedlund]]\n* [[Florence Lawrence]] as At the Beach\n* [[Marion Leonard]]\n* [[Mack Sennett]] as Policeman\n* [[Harry Solter]] as At the Beach\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0000785|Where the Breakers Roar}}\n\n{{D. W. Griffith |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Where The Breakers Roar}}\n[[Category:1908 films]]\n[[Category:1908 drama films]]\n[[Category:1908 short films]]\n[[Category:American fi